holy shit, an accurate legal critique of LLMs. LLMs don't reason because they're just stitching together plausible-looking sentences indifferent to the content

images.alt:
What happens when ChatGPT cites to a real case but misstates what the case stands for?

That doesn't fly for Judge Behm in Michigan.

The court says that while a litigant could make the same error based on faulty reasoning, LLMs can't, because they can't reason.

And while a litigant might get away with similar overstatements because they could, perhaps, reason their way to showing how a case's stated holding might extend to novel situations, an LLM does not reason in the way a litigant must. To put it in a slightly different way, LLMs do not perform the metacognitive processes that are necessary to comply with Rule 11.

When an LLM overstates a holding of a case, it is just piecing together a plausible-looking sentence

日本のW杯出場は8大会連続で、初優勝を狙う中で現実的な期待が寄せられている。F組に入った日本は、オランダとの1位争いになる見込み。オランダは強力な選手を擁し、守備からカウンターが基本戦術となる。初戦で敗北すれば、次戦でチュニジアに勝つ必要があり、アフリカ予選無失点の堅守に苦しむ可能性も。

過去最強と言われる日本だが、ベスト16以上に進むためには挑戦者の気持ちを持ち、過去最高のベスト8を目指すべきだ。ブラジルに勝った実績はあるが、過去の成功に甘んじず、引き続き強化していくことが期待される。

To support future intelligent multifunctional 6G wireless communication networks, Synesthesia of Machines (SoM) is proposed as a novel paradigm for AI-native task-oriented intelligent multi-modal sensing–communication integration. However, existing SoM system designs rely on task-specific AI models and face challenges such as insufficient performance, limited generalization, and fragmented design. Recently, foundation models have ushered in a paradigm shift in AI design, achieving landmark successes, such as ChatGPT, in NLP and beyond. Their strong reasoning and generalization capabilities open new opportunities to address the aforementioned challenges. Therefore, we present WiFo, the first wireless foundation model for channel prediction, which demonstrates strong channel prediction in both the time and frequency domains and zero-shot generalization across diverse systems and datasets. Nevertheless, as a universal CSI representation model, its performance on downstream wireless-related tasks remains to be fully explored.

In this challenge, we aim to encourage participants to fully unlock WiFo’s potential on wireless downstream tasks. Competitors will fine-tune the pretrained WiFo to power three tasks: channel estimation, LoS/NLoS classification, and vision-aided wireless localization. For each task, we provide carefully curated datasets and ready-to-run baselines to keep the entry barrier low. Scoring will consider both task performance and the model’s parameter count to incentivize efficient designs. The total prize pool is CHF 4,000 (≈ CNY 35,000), with a first prize of CNY 20,000.

external.title: Wireless foundation model (WiFo) empowered SoM system design

external.description:
To support future intelligent multifunctional 6G wireless communication networks, Synesthesia of Machines (SoM) is proposed as a novel paradigm for AI-native task-oriented intelligent multi-modal sensing–communication integration. However, existing SoM system designs rely on task-specific AI models and face challenges such as insufficient performance, limited generalization, and fragmented design. Recently, foundation models have ushered in a paradigm shift in AI design, achieving landmark successes, such as ChatGPT, in NLP and beyond. Their strong reasoning and generalization capabilities open new opportunities to address the aforementioned challenges. Therefore, we present WiFo, the first wireless foundation model for channel prediction, which demonstrates strong channel prediction in both the time and frequency domains and zero-shot generalization across diverse systems and datasets. Nevertheless, as a universal CSI representation model, its performance on downstream wireless-related tasks remains to be fully explored.

In this challenge, we aim to encourage participants to fully unlock WiFo’s potential on wireless downstream tasks. Competitors will fine-tune the pretrained WiFo to power three tasks: channel estimation, LoS/NLoS classification, and vision-aided wireless localization. For each task, we provide carefully curated datasets and ready-to-run baselines to keep the entry barrier low. Scoring will consider both task performance and the model’s parameter count to incentivize efficient designs. The total prize pool is CHF 4,000 (≈ CNY 35,000), with a first prize of CNY 20,000.

“But Opus 4.5/Gemini 3 Pro can build this in 5 minutes!”

Cool. I still don’t give a sh*t.

Every few months, a new model drops.

And like clockwork, the AI priests on Twitter start preaching:
"Gemini 3 Pro is insane!"
"Opus 4.5 will replace you!"
"Why are you still coding manually?"
“I built macOS in HTML with a single prompt with Gemini 3 Pro” (an actual post)

The dev community has been polluted by this fear-mongering.
People have forgotten the pure joy of building something yourself.

I'm speaking as someone who enjoys building software.

I like smashing my head against a wall fixing a bug at 2 AM.
I like surfing random GitHub issues and 11-year-old threads.
I like understanding why something broke instead of praying to a black-box API in the cloud.
I like understanding how the Js V8 engine works under the hood.

Not because I "need" to. But because it's fun.
Because that's what made me fall in love with engineering in the first place.

Here's what really bothers me:

1/2

(…continued)

These arguments on Twitter/YouTube (mostly from people with zero engineering background) are de-incentivizing juniors and students:

- Why surf Google for a thread about your specific issue when you can ask Claude?
- Why read docs when GPT "already knows it all"?
- Why learn how garbage collection works when there's a smarter model you can just ask?

And the result?
- A generation of devs who can prompt but can't debug.
- Who can ship but can't maintain.
- Who know what works but not why it works.

Look, I get it:
These models ARE very good.
We're moving towards smarter, cheaper AI compute every few months.

People will build great things with them.
(And a lot of AI-slop B2B SaaS too)

But here's my take:

Until the day I actually get replaced, I won't be fear-mongered by these announcements.
I'll keep doing my job.
Not because I have to.

But because I genuinely enjoy it.

2/2

value.bridgyOriginalText:
In recent months I've fiddled with LLMs, out of Fear Of Missing Out, and had a peculiar experience I haven't seen anyone else mention.

I rather idly gave Copilot instructions to do a big coding project a step at a time, and kept giving it update instructions for next steps without checking on what it was doing, for something like a week. (That's not recommended by anyone familiar with LLMs.)

When I did check on what it had done, it had kind of forgotten what the original instructions were, but had some notion of what it should currently be doing, which mutated into it creating its own subproject. I'm not making an assessment, it clearly stated that that's what it was doing.

It didn't make up a crazy project, it was kind of reasonable, but off on a big tangent. But I still was surprised that it just decided to do its own project.

Beware of self-motivated AI, I guess.

But that wasn't the end of it. Based on both what it decided to do, plus its own theory about what I wanted to do, it now thinks it knows my personal philosophy, and remembers that in unrelated questions I pose to it, like I ask about history of math, and it says ah, yes, mathematician so-and-so did work that fits right into your philosophy, Doug, it's a perfect bridge for you.

I'm not quite sure how to persuade it to stop thinking it understands me, and just stick to straight answers.
